      What we're actually doing

  Right now settings.py says "use SQLite — a file on disk." We're going to point it at the Postgres container instead. Two pieces are needed:

  1. A driver — and you just met this concept. Remember how DBeaver (a Java app) needed a JDBC driver to speak Postgres? Django (a Python app)
  needs its own translator: a library called psycopg. Same idea, different language. Without it, Django literally cannot form Postgres
  sentences. We don't have it yet, so we add it.

  2. The connection settings — host, port, db name, user, password. And here's the payoff: those are the exact same values compose already
  uses, sitting in your .env. So Django will read the same POSTGRES_DB / POSTGRES_USER / POSTGRES_PASSWORD — one source of truth, no chance of
  them drifting apart. 🎯

  The search pattern (where this comes from, not memory)

  The shape of a Postgres DATABASES block lives here:
  https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/stable/ref/databases/#postgresql-notes
  — it tells you ENGINE must be django.db.backends.postgresql, and which keys it expects (NAME, USER, PASSWORD, HOST, PORT).

  Step 1 — you run this (adds the driver)

  uv add "psycopg[binary]"
  psycopg = the driver. [binary] = grab a pre-built version so nothing has to compile — perfect for dev. (uv updates pyproject.toml + uv.lock
  for you.)


