  Notice everything pulls from .env with config() — the same pattern you already had for REDIS_URL. Consistent, no secrets in the file.

  The one forward-looking choice — HOST

  I gave HOST a default of 127.0.0.1 instead of hardcoding it. Why bother? Because the day we put Django itself inside a container (later in
  this phase), Django won't reach Postgres at 127.0.0.1 anymore — inside Docker's network, the address becomes the service name db. By making
  it config("POSTGRES_HOST", default=...), we'll switch that with a single .env line, zero code changes. We're leaving a door open for our
  future selves. That's the parity mindset.

  Now — the proof it works

  Django's built-in apps (admin, auth, sessions) need their tables created. Right now your Postgres dashboard database is empty. Let's fill it:

  python manage.py migrate

  Watch the output — you'll see a list of Applying ... OK lines. Each one is Django creating a table inside your Postgres container.

  Then the payoff 🎁

  After it finishes, go back to DBeaver, right-click your dashboard connection → Refresh (or press F5), and expand:
  dashboard → Schemas → public → Tables

  You'll see the tables Django just made (auth_user, django_migrations, etc.) — appearing in a totally separate tool. That's the moment it all
  connects: Django wrote to the same database DBeaver is reading.


