● No worries — this is a "later" thing, but it's a good question. Let me make it concrete.

  The key idea: where Django lives changes how it finds Postgres

  Right now: Django runs on your laptop. Postgres runs in a container. Django finds Postgres by ringing the inside doorbell — 127.0.0.1. ✅
  This works today.

  Later in this phase: we'll put Django itself inside a container too. Now both Django and Postgres are inside "Docker's world" — like two
  rooms in the same hotel.

  Here's the catch: inside the hotel, you don't dial the street address to reach the room next door — you call it by its room name. And
  Postgres's room name is already set: it's db (the service name at the top of your docker-compose.yml).

  services:
    db:        ← THIS is the room name
      image: postgres:16

  So the address Django uses to reach Postgres changes depending on where Django is sitting:

  ┌────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┐
  │     Where Django runs      │ Address it uses for Postgres │
  ├────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
  │ On your laptop (today)     │ 127.0.0.1                    │
  ├────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
  │ Inside a container (later) │ db                           │
  └────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────┘

  So why the default= trick?

  If I had hardcoded "HOST": "127.0.0.1" straight into the code, then the day we move Django into a container, that line would be wrong — and
  you'd have to edit the Python code to fix it.

  Instead I wrote config("POSTGRES_HOST", default="127.0.0.1"). That means:
  - "Look in .env for POSTGRES_HOST. If it's not there, just use 127.0.0.1."
  - Today: .env has no POSTGRES_HOST, so it uses the default 127.0.0.1. Works now. ✅
  - Later: we add one line to .env → POSTGRES_HOST=db → done. No code change.

  The lesson (this is the real takeaway)

  We left a door open for our future selves. Instead of nailing a value into the code, we made it adjustable from .env. When the situation
  changes, you flip a setting, not rewrite code. That's a habit good engineers build everywhere.

  You don't need to do anything about this now — it's already set up correctly. It'll just quietly work when we get there. 🙂





    
